s that farming is the best livelihood for a philosopher; and there is much more.Proof that farming is ultimately a state of mind we should all cultivate, How to Be a Farmer will charm anyone who loves nature or its fruits.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAgriculture, AncientzGreecexLiterary collections. 0aAgriculture, AncientzRomexLiterary collections. 0aClassical literaturevTranslations into English. 0aCountry lifezGreecexLiterary collections. 0aCountry lifezRomexLiterary collections. 0aFarm lifezGreecevLiterary collections. 0aFarm lifezRomevLiterary collections. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAgriculture (Chinese mythology).  aAgriculture.  aAgronomy.  aAnecdote.  aAnimal welfare.  aArval Brethren.  aAulularia.  aAutoeroticism.  aBarley water.  aBarley.  aBiodynamic agriculture.  aBonus Eventus.  aBread.  aBumper crop.  aBy Nature.  aCattle.  aChaff (countermeasure).  aCleanthes.  aCompost.  aConfectionery.  aCoriander.  aCountry Living.  aCuisine.  aCustomer.  aDe Agri Cultura.  aDe rerum natura.  aDiogenes of Sinope.  aDivinity (academic discipline).  aEarthenware.  aEven working.  aFamily farm.  aFirewood.  aFlour.  aFodder.  aGaius Furius Chresimus.  aGrazing.  aGroat (grain).  aHesiod.  aHighland cattle.  aHousehold.  aKeeping up with the Joneses.  aLatifundium.  aLife on Land.  aLifestyle (sociology).  aLivelihood.  aLivestock.  aLoaf.  aLoeb Classical Library.  aLongus.  aLucretius.  aLympha.  aManual labour.  aManure.  aMeal.  aMilitary tribune.  aMillet.  aMoral development.  aMy Neighbor.  aNew Harvest.  aNobility.  aOx.  aParilia.  aPasture.  aPhilosopher.  aPhilosophy.  aPilumnus.  aPlautus.  aPlebs.  aPliny 